<Base title="About — Dr. Lior Tabansky" description="Dr. Lior Tabansky works where defense innovation, AI, and national resilience meet — turning deep expertise into decisions governments and investors can act on." lang="en" dir="ltr">
  <section class="hero"><div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1>Strategy that survives contact with reality.</h1>
    <p class="sub">I work at the meeting point of defense innovation, artificial intelligence, and national resilience — for governments and investors who need judgment they can act on, not another report.</p>
  </div></section>
  <section><div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">The through-line</p>
    <p>My grounding is operational. I served in an elite Israel Air Force technology unit built around a major innovation for multi-domain warfare — where I learned that advantage comes from how technology meets organization, not from the technology alone. That question has driven my work since.</p>
    <p>I built the argument into a theory of cyber-power — presented at NATO's Cooperative Cyber Defence Centre of Excellence and set out in <em>Cybersecurity in Israel</em> (Springer), written with Major General Isaac Ben-Israel. Then I put it to work. As Director of Strategy on an advisory to the Government of Singapore, I authored the vision, goals, and 70+ recommendations behind the country's National Cybersecurity Strategy. In World Bank–backed work, I led critical-infrastructure resilience roadmaps across a dozen countries in Europe, Asia, and Africa, and turned a Tel Aviv University research practice into a self-funding professional-services unit.</p>
    <p>The through-line is commercial as much as strategic. I've designed executive programs that closed the gap between boards and cyber risk, and I advise investors and governments on where defense and AI innovation actually creates value — and where it only looks like it does.</p>
  </div></section>
  <section><div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">How I work — from first principles</p>
    <p>When the playbooks don't fit — and at the frontier they rarely do — I reason from first principles. I map the whole system, separate signal from noise, and, as Michael Porter put it, decide what not to do. To do that rigorously, I developed a method to analyze an entire sector as a complex socio-technical-economic system, drawing on complexity science, network science, public policy, and safety engineering.</p>
    <p>It's also why I'm wary of frontier-model theater. AI can deliver insight, decision support, and autonomy — but only once an organization is built to use it. The hard part was never the model.</p>
  </div></section>
  <section><div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">Selected engagements</p>
    <p>Public anchors: Singapore's National Cybersecurity Strategy and capacity work with the World Bank. Most of what I do is private — for governments and investors who value discretion.</p>
  </div></section>
  <section><div class="wrap">
